  {
    title:
      "Dermo-DOCTOR: A framework for concurrent skin lesion detection and recognition using a deep convolutional neural network with end-to-end dual encoders",
    authors:
      "M K Hasan, S Roy, C Mondal, M A Alam, M T E Elahi, A Dutta, S M T U Raju, M T Jawad, M Ahmad",
    venue: "Biomedical Signal Processing and Control",
    year: "2021",
    link: "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1746809421002585",
    abstract: `
<strong>Background and Objective:</strong> Automated skin lesion analysis for simultaneous detection and recognition remains challenging due to inter-class homogeneity and intra-class heterogeneity, which limit the generalization capability of single convolutional neural network (CNN) models trained on small datasets.

<br><br><strong>Methods:</strong> We propose Dermo-DOCTOR, an end-to-end deep CNN framework for simultaneous lesion detection and classification using a dual-encoder architecture. Feature maps from both encoders are fused channel-wise to create a fused feature representation that supports lesion segmentation through a decoding network. For recognition, features from both encoders and the fused representation are aggregated through fully connected layers to determine the final lesion class. The framework was trained and evaluated on the ISIC-2016 and ISIC-2017 benchmark datasets.

<br><br><strong>Results:</strong> The model achieved mean intersection-over-union scores of 85.0% and 80.0% on the ISIC-2016 and ISIC-2017 test datasets, respectively. For lesion classification, the system obtained areas under the receiver operating characteristic curve of 0.98 and 0.91 on the two datasets. These results outperform several previously reported approaches for automated skin lesion detection and recognition.

<br><br><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Dermo-DOCTOR demonstrates strong performance for both segmentation and recognition tasks, even with limited training data, suggesting its potential as a computer-aided diagnostic support tool for dermatological image analysis.
`,
